Data preprocessing¶

Importing dataset and selecting first 10 features¶

In [20]:
breast_cancer = datasets.load_breast_cancer()
data = pd.DataFrame(data=breast_cancer.data, columns=breast_cancer.feature_names)
data['target'] = breast_cancer.target
feature_names = ['mean radius', 'mean texture', 'mean perimeter', 'mean area',
       'mean smoothness', 'mean compactness', 'mean concavity',
       'mean concave points', 'mean symmetry', 'mean fractal dimension', 'target']
data = data[feature_names]

Splitting into training and testing data¶

In [21]:
np.random.seed(3035347457)
df_train,df_test = train_test_split(data,test_size=0.2)
X_train = df_train.iloc[:, 0:-1].values
y_train = df_train.iloc[:, -1].values
X_test = df_test.iloc[:, 0:-1].values
y_test = df_test.iloc[:, -1].values

1. Decision Tree Classifier¶

Splitting with Gini Impurity¶

In [23]:
dt1 = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='gini', max_depth=3)
dt1.fit(X_train, y_train)

print('The Acc on training set:', accuracy_score(y_train,dt1.predict(X_train)))
print('The Acc on testing set:', accuracy_score(y_test,dt1.predict(X_test)))

train_results['DT-Gini'] = accuracy_score(y_train,dt1.predict(X_train))
test_results['DT-Gini'] = accuracy_score(y_test,dt1.predict(X_test))

5. Post-hoc Interpretability analysis¶

Model Selection¶

  • The first step for this section is the decision process for which classifier we will choose as the most-accurate model. Given below are the train, test and average ($\frac{train + test}{2}$) accuracies for the various classifiers.
In [72]:
# train_results, test_results
for k in train_results:
    print(f"{k}: {np.round(train_results[k], 2)} | {np.round(test_results[k], 2)} | {np.round((train_results[k]+test_results[k])/2, 4)}")

DT-Gini: 0.97 | 0.91 | 0.9397
DT-Entropy: 0.96 | 0.91 | 0.9386
RF: 1.0 | 0.96 | 0.9825
GB: 1.0 | 0.96 | 0.9781
SVM-Linear: 0.91 | 0.96 | 0.933
SVM-RBF: 0.88 | 0.86 | 0.8705
MLP: 0.9 | 0.9 | 0.9034
  • From the above results, we can clearly see that RF (Random Forest), has the best results for training, testing and average accuracies. $\therefore$ we select Random Forest as the most accurate black-box model.

Global Interpretability¶

Variable Importance¶

  • First, we evaluate feature importance through the use of the eli5 library.
  • If a feature is important, a small change in the value will have significantly affect the prediction
  • From the below figure, we observe the features ranked in descending order of importance

Partial Dependence Plot¶

  • Partial dependence plots are used to understand the relation between individual features and the response
  • Relationships can be linear, monotonic, exponential or more complex

Local Interpretability¶

LIME¶

  • The explanation of individual datapoints is carried out with the help of Local interpretable model-agnostic explanations (LIME).
  • Explanations are done with approximations of the black-box model with more interpretable models, usually GLMs

SHAP¶

  • Given a black-box model and one sample, SHAP attempts to decompose the effects of each feature on the differenc between the predicted value and the expected value of the model where the expectation is taken over the training examples (averaged training predictions).
  • We can explain the predictions in either training or testing set but the explainer should be defined on the training set. In this section, we explain the training set.
In [99]:
